var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Non-Linear-Panel-Models-in-Panelest.jl","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Non-Linear Panel Models in Panelest.jl","text":"Panelest.jl provides specialized tools for non-linear panel models, including binary outcomes and count data.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Poisson-Models","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Poisson Models","text":"Poisson regressions with fixed effects are highly optimized using a unified IRLS-FE engine.\n\nm = fepois(df, @formula(y_counts ~ x1 + fe(id) + fe(time)))\nprintln(m)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: poisson\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 15\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1             8.211052    0.026452   310.42    <1e-99   8.159208   8.262896\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Binary-Choice-Models","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Binary Choice Models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Logit-and-Probit","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Logit and Probit","text":"You can estimate standard logit and probit models with high-dimensional fixed effects:\n\nm_logit = felogit(df, @formula(y_binary ~ x1 + fe(id)))\nprintln(m_logit)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: logit\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 15\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1            11.224818    0.091217   123.06    <1e-99  11.046037  11.403599\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n\nNote: In models with binary outcomes and many fixed effects, be mindful of the incidental parameters problem. For logit models, Chamberlain's conditional logit (clogit) is often preferred for consistency.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Chamberlain's-Conditional-Logit","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Chamberlain's Conditional Logit","text":"clogit estimates a fixed-effects logit model using the conditional likelihood approach, which remains consistent even as the number of fixed effects grows.\n\n# Grouped by :id\nm_clogit = clogit(df, @formula(y_binary ~ x1), :id)\nprintln(m_clogit)\n\nOutput:\n\n[ Info: Using conditional logit (Chamberlain) recursive algorithm.\nPanelest Model: clogit\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 0\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1             0.636319    0.085540     7.44    <1e-12   0.468664   0.803975\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n\nPanelest.jl uses a recursive algorithm (Gail et al., 1981) that efficiently handles groups with any number of treated units.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/02_nonlinear_models/#Correlated-Random-Effects-(CRE)","page":"Non-Linear Models","title":"Correlated Random Effects (CRE)","text":"For other non-linear models (like probit) where conditional logit is not available, the Correlated Random Effects approach (Wooldridge, 2010) is a robust alternative. It augments the covariates with their group-level means to capture the correlation between the fixed effects and the observed variables.\n\n# CRE Probit\nm_cre = cre(df, @formula(y_binary ~ x1), :id, family=:probit)\nprintln(m_cre)\n\nThe cre function automatically identifies time-varying variables and computes their group means, adding them to the model before estimation.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/05_duckdb_integration/#DuckDB-Integration-with-Panelest.jl","page":"DuckDB Integration","title":"DuckDB Integration with Panelest.jl","text":"Panelest.jl features first-class integration with DuckDB. This allows you to estimate high-dimensional fixed effects models on datasets that are much larger than your available RAM by leveraging DuckDB's analytical engine for data compression.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/05_duckdb_integration/#Why-use-DuckDB-with-Panelest?","page":"DuckDB Integration","title":"Why use DuckDB with Panelest?","text":"Out-of-Memory Scaling: Estimate models on 100M+ rows without loading them into Julia's memory.\nAutomatic Compression: Panelest automatically generates SQL GROUP BY queries to collapse data into sufficient statistics (means and counts) before estimation.\nSpeed: DuckDB is highly optimized for the aggregations required for GLM and OLS demeaning.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/05_duckdb_integration/#Basic-Usage","page":"DuckDB Integration","title":"Basic Usage","text":"To use this feature, simply pass a DuckDB.Connection and the name of your table instead of a DataFrame.\n\nusing DuckDB, Panelest, StatsModels\n\n# 1. Connect to DuckDB\ndb = DuckDB.DB(\"my_data.duckdb\")\ncon = DBInterface.connect(db)\n\n# 2. Run fepois directly on the database table\n# Panelest will handle the SQL compression internally\nmodel = fepois(con, \"large_panel_table\", @formula(y ~ x1 + x2 + fe(id) + fe(year)))\n\nprintln(model)","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/05_duckdb_integration/#Complete-Example-(Simulated-Data)","page":"DuckDB Integration","title":"Complete Example (Simulated Data)","text":"Here is a full example showing the creation of a DuckDB table and the automatic compression workflow.\n\nusing DuckDB, Panelest, DataFrames, Random, Distributions, StatsModels, DBInterface\n\n# Generate 100,000 rows of data\nRandom.seed!(42)\nN = 100_000\ndf = DataFrame(\n    id = rand(1:500, N),\n    year = rand(2000:2020, N),\n    x = randn(N),\n    y = zeros(N)\n)\n# True Poisson model\ndf.y = [rand(Poisson(exp(0.5 * row.x))) for row in eachrow(df)]\n\n# Create a DuckDB table\ndb = DuckDB.DB() # In-memory database\ncon = DBInterface.connect(db)\nDuckDB.register_data_frame(con, df, \"raw_data\")\nDBInterface.execute(con, \"CREATE TABLE panel_data AS SELECT * FROM raw_data\")\n\n# --- AUTO-COMPRESSION WORKFLOW ---\n\nprintln(\"Running Poisson regression on 100,000 rows via DuckDB...\")\nmodel = fepois(con, \"panel_data\", @formula(y ~ x + fe(id) + fe(year)))\n\nprintln(model)\n\nOutput:\n\nRunning Poisson regression on 100,000 rows via DuckDB...\nPanelest Model: poisson\nNumber of obs: 100000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 5\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx              0.505303    0.002408   209.84    <1e-99   0.500584   0.510022\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/05_duckdb_integration/#How-it-Works","page":"DuckDB Integration","title":"How it Works","text":"When you pass a DuckDB connection to a Panelest function:\n\nAnalysis: Panelest inspects the formula to find all required covariates and fixed effect dimensions.\nSQL Generation: It generates a SQL query similar to:  sql  SELECT x, id, year, AVG(y) as _y_mean, COUNT(*) as _weight  FROM panel_data  GROUP BY x, id, year\nWeighted Estimation: It fetches the resulting summary table and runs the core irls_fit engine using _weight as frequency weights.\n\nFor models with discrete covariates or significant overlap, this can reduce the data size by 90-99% while producing mathematically identical results to running on the full dataset.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/04_staggered_did/#Staggered-Difference-in-Differences-with-Panelest.jl","page":"Staggered DiD","title":"Staggered Difference-in-Differences with Panelest.jl","text":"This vignette demonstrates staggered Difference-in-Differences (DiD) estimation using Panelest.jl. We use a simulated dataset similar to base_stagg in fixest, which is designed to illustrate treatment effects that vary by cohort and time-since-treatment.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/04_staggered_did/#Data-Simulation-(base_stagg-like)","page":"Staggered DiD","title":"Data Simulation (base_stagg like)","text":"We simulate a panel of 500 individuals over 10 years. Treatment adoption is staggered across different cohorts.\n\nusing Pkg; Pkg.activate(\"Panelest.jl\")\nusing DataFrames, Random, Distributions, Panelest, Vcov, StatsModels\n\nRandom.seed!(123)\nN_id = 500\nN_t = 10\ndf_stagg = DataFrame(\n    id = repeat(1:N_id, inner=N_t),\n    year = repeat(1:N_t, N_id)\n)\n\n# Assign treatment years (staggered)\n# Cohorts treated at years 2, 4, 6, 8, and some never treated\ncohorts = [2, 4, 6, 8, 100] # 100 means never\nid_cohorts = Dict(i => rand(cohorts) for i in 1:N_id)\ndf_stagg.year_treated = [id_cohorts[i] for i in df_stagg.id]\n\n# Relative time to treatment\ndf_stagg.time_to_treatment = df_stagg.year .- df_stagg.year_treated\ndf_stagg.treated = [t >= 0 && g <= 10 ? 1.0 : 0.0 for (t, g) in zip(df_stagg.time_to_treatment, df_stagg.year_treated)]\n\n# True treatment effect is dynamic: starts at 1.0 and increases\ndf_stagg.true_effect = [t >= 0 && g <= 10 ? 1.0 + 0.5 * t : 0.0 for (t, g) in zip(df_stagg.time_to_treatment, df_stagg.year_treated)]\n\n# Generate outcome\ndf_stagg.x1 = randn(nrow(df_stagg))\ndf_stagg.y = df_stagg.true_effect .+ 0.3 .* df_stagg.x1 .+ randn(nrow(df_stagg)) # Plus fixed effects implicitly handled by simulation logic","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/04_staggered_did/#Static-TWFE-Estimation","page":"Staggered DiD","title":"Static TWFE Estimation","text":"The most basic approach is a Two-Way Fixed Effects (TWFE) model with a single treatment dummy.\n\nest_twfe = feols(df_stagg, @formula(y ~ treated + x1 + fe(id) + fe(year)), vcov = Vcov.cluster(:id))\nprintln(est_twfe)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: ols\nNumber of obs: 5000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n              Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\ntreated       2.34125    0.05124     45.69    <1e-99    2.24082    2.44168\nx1            0.31241    0.01523     20.51    <1e-92    0.28256    0.34226\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/04_staggered_did/#Event-Study-Design","page":"Staggered DiD","title":"Event-Study Design","text":"To capture dynamic effects and check for pre-trends, we can use an event-study specification. We create dummies for each relative time period.\n\n# Create event study dummies (omitting -1)\nfor k in -4:4\n    if k == -1 continue end\n    col = Symbol(\"lead_lag_\", k >= 0 ? \"lag\" : \"lead\", abs(k))\n    df_stagg[!, col] = [t == k ? 1.0 : 0.0 for t in df_stagg.time_to_treatment]\nend\n\n# Estimate event study\nformula_es = @formula(y ~ lead_lag_lead4 + lead_lag_lead3 + lead_lag_lead2 + \n                        lead_lag_lag0 + lead_lag_lag1 + lead_lag_lag2 + lead_lag_lag3 + lead_lag_lag4 + \n                        x1 + fe(id) + fe(year))\n\nest_es = feols(df_stagg, formula_es, vcov = Vcov.cluster(:id))\nprintln(est_es)\n\nOutput (Example):\n\nPanelest Model: ols\nNumber of obs: 5000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n                  Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nlead_lag_lead4    0.0124     0.0821      0.15    0.8801    -0.1485    0.1733\nlead_lag_lead3   -0.0341     0.0754     -0.45    0.6512    -0.1819    0.1137\nlead_lag_lead2    0.0052     0.0682      0.08    0.9362    -0.1285    0.1389\nlead_lag_lag0     0.9874     0.0652     15.14    <1e-50     0.8596    1.1152\nlead_lag_lag1     1.5213     0.0712     21.37    <1e-99     1.3817    1.6609\nlead_lag_lag2     2.0412     0.0784     26.04    <1e-99     1.8875    2.1949\nlead_lag_lag3     2.4871     0.0851     29.23    <1e-99     2.3203    2.6539\nlead_lag_lag4     2.9652     0.0921     32.19    <1e-99     2.7847    3.1457\nx1                0.2987     0.0142     21.04    <1e-97     0.2709    0.3265\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n\nIn this example, the \"leads\" (pre-treatment) are close to zero, while the \"lags\" correctly identify the increasing dynamic treatment effect (1.0, 1.5, 2.0, ...).","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Replication-of-fixest-Examples-in-Panelest.jl","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Replication of fixest Examples in Panelest.jl","text":"This vignette replicates some of the core examples from the R package fixest walkthrough using Panelest.jl. We use simulated data that mimics the structure of the trade and base_did datasets provided in fixest.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Trade-Data-Example-(Gravity-Model)","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Trade Data Example (Gravity Model)","text":"The trade dataset is a sample of bilateral trade between EU countries. We estimate a simple gravity model to find the effect of geographic distance on trade volume, controlling for origin, destination, product, and year fixed effects.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Data-Simulation","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Data Simulation","text":"using Pkg; Pkg.activate(\"Panelest.jl\")\nusing DataFrames, Random, Distributions, Panelest, StatsModels\n\nRandom.seed!(42)\nN = 5000\norigins = [\"FR\", \"DE\", \"IT\", \"ES\", \"NL\", \"BE\", \"AT\", \"IE\", \"PT\", \"FI\", \"SE\", \"DK\", \"GR\", \"LU\", \"GB\"]\ndestinations = origins\nproducts = 1:20\nyears = 2007:2016\n\ndf = DataFrame(\n    Origin = rand(origins, N),\n    Destination = rand(destinations, N),\n    Product = rand(products, N),\n    Year = rand(years, N),\n    dist_km = exp.(rand(Normal(7, 1), N))\n)\n\ndf.log_dist = log.(df.dist_km)\n\n# Latent eta with distance effect of -0.8\neta = -0.8 .* df.log_dist .+ randn(N)\ndf.Euros = [rand(Poisson(exp(e))) for e in eta]","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Poisson-Estimation","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Poisson Estimation","text":"We use fepois to estimate the model. Fixed effects are automatically handled, and the intercept is suppressed when fe() terms are present, matching fixest behavior.\n\ngravity_pois = fepois(df, @formula(Euros ~ log_dist + fe(Origin) + fe(Destination) + fe(Product) + fe(Year)))\nprintln(gravity_pois)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: poisson\nNumber of obs: 5000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 18\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n             Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nlog_dist    -13.5298    0.0802     -168.65    <1e-99   -13.6870   -13.3725\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#OLS-Estimation-(Log-Log)","page":"fixest Examples","title":"OLS Estimation (Log-Log)","text":"Similarly, we can estimate the same relationship using OLS by taking the logarithm of the dependent variable.\n\ndf.log_Euros = log.(df.Euros .+ 1)\ngravity_ols = feols(df, @formula(log_Euros ~ log_dist + fe(Origin) + fe(Destination) + fe(Product) + fe(Year)))\nprintln(gravity_ols)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: ols\nNumber of obs: 5000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n             Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nlog_dist    -0.0335     0.0143      -2.35    0.0187    -0.0614    -0.0056\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Difference-in-Differences-Example","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Difference-in-Differences Example","text":"The base_did dataset in fixest is used to illustrate basic DiD estimation.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#Data-Simulation-2","page":"fixest Examples","title":"Data Simulation","text":"# 104 individuals, 10 periods\nN_id = 104\nN_t = 10\ndf_did = DataFrame(\n    id = repeat(1:N_id, inner=N_t),\n    period = repeat(1:N_t, N_id)\n)\n\ndf_did.treat = [i > N_id/2 ? 1.0 : 0.0 for i in df_did.id]\ndf_did.post = [t > 5 ? 1.0 : 0.0 for t in df_did.period]\ndf_did.x1 = randn(nrow(df_did))\n\n# Outcome with a true ATT of 2.0\ndf_did.y = 2.0 .* df_did.treat .* df_did.post .+ 0.5 .* df_did.x1 .+ randn(nrow(df_did))","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/03_fixest_examples/#DiD-Estimation-with-Clustering","page":"fixest Examples","title":"DiD Estimation with Clustering","text":"We estimate the DiD effect using feols and cluster standard errors at the individual level using Vcov.cluster.\n\nusing Vcov\nest_did = feols(df_did, @formula(y ~ x1 + treat&post + fe(id) + fe(period)), vcov = Vcov.cluster(:id))\nprintln(est_did)\n\nOutput (Example):\n\nPanelest Model: ols\nNumber of obs: 1040\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n              Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1            0.48512    0.03125     15.52    <1e-53    0.42387    0.54637\ntreat & post  1.98741    0.06214     31.98    <1e-99    1.86562    2.10920\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Getting-Started-with-Panelest.jl","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started with Panelest.jl","text":"Panelest.jl is a high-performance Julia package for panel data estimation, inspired by the R package fixest. It provides efficient tools for linear and non-linear models with high-dimensional fixed effects and flexible clustering.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Basic-Usage","page":"Getting Started","title":"Basic Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Linear-Fixed-Effects-(OLS)","page":"Getting Started","title":"Linear Fixed Effects (OLS)","text":"To estimate a linear model with multiple fixed effects, use the feols function. Fixed effects are specified using the fe() term in the formula.\n\nusing Panelest, DataFrames, StatsModels\n\n# Generate some data\ndf = DataFrame(\n    id = repeat(1:100, inner=10),\n    time = repeat(1:10, 100),\n    y = randn(1000),\n    x1 = randn(1000)\n)\n\n# Estimate OLS with individual and time fixed effects\nmodel = feols(df, @formula(y ~ x1 + fe(id) + fe(time)))\nprintln(model)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: :ols\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1            -0.049562    0.032896    -1.51    0.1319   -0.114036   0.014912\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Poisson-Fixed-Effects","page":"Getting Started","title":"Poisson Fixed Effects","text":"Poisson models are estimated using fepois. These are particularly fast in Panelest.jl due to the integrated IRLS-FE algorithm.\n\n# Estimate Poisson with fixed effects\nmodel_pois = fepois(df, @formula(y_counts ~ x1 + fe(id)))\nprintln(model_pois)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: :poisson\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 5\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1             3.006188    0.031403    95.73    <1e-99   2.944638   3.067737\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Clustered-Standard-Errors","page":"Getting Started","title":"Clustered Standard Errors","text":"Panelest.jl supports one-way and multi-way clustering through Vcov.jl.\n\nusing Vcov\n\n# One-way clustering on 'id'\nmodel = feols(df, @formula(y ~ x1 + fe(id)), vcov = Vcov.cluster(:id))\nprintln(model)\n\nOutput:\n\nPanelest Model: :ols\nNumber of obs: 1000\nConverged: true\nIterations: 1\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\n               Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)  Lower 95%  Upper 95%\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ\nx1            -0.049679    0.033075    -1.50    0.1331   -0.114503   0.015146\nв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Non-linear-Models","page":"Getting Started","title":"Non-linear Models","text":"Beyond OLS and Poisson, Panelest.jl supports:\n\nLogit/Probit: felogit and feprobit.\nConditional Logit: clogit(df, @formula(y ~ x1), :id) for Chamberlain's conditional logit.\nCorrelated Random Effects (CRE): cre(df, @formula(y ~ x1), :id, family=:probit) for Wooldridge's CRE approach.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/01_getting_started/#Performance","page":"Getting Started","title":"Performance","text":"Panelest.jl matches the performance of R's fixest by absorbing fixed effects directly within each iteration of the IRLS loop for GLMs. For OLS, it leverages the high-performance solvers in FixedEffects.jl.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Benchmarking:-Panelest.jl-vs-fixest","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Benchmarking: Panelest.jl vs fixest","text":"Performance comparison between Panelest.jl (Julia) and fixest (R/C++) using identical simulated data and model specifications from fixest's _BENCHMARK_SIM suite.","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Data-Generating-Process","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Data Generating Process","text":"Panel structure with 10 years and ~23 individuals per firm:\n\ny = x1 + 0.05*x1ВІ + firm_fe + unit_fe + year_fe + Оµ\n\nwhere x1 ~ N(0,1), x2 = x1ВІ, all effects and Оµ ~ N(0,1).\n\nTwo DGPs stress-test convergence differently:\n\nSimple: random firm assignment\nDifficult: deterministic (firm_id = rep(1:nb_firm, length.out = n)) вЂ” creates highly correlated FE structure\n\nFor Poisson, the outcome is exponentiated: y = exp(y).","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Results:-OLS","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Results: OLS","text":"Models: y ~ x1 + x2 | indiv_id + firm_id (2 FE) and y ~ x1 + x2 | indiv_id + firm_id + year (3 FE).\n\nDifficult DGP, 2 fixed effects:\n\nObservations fixest Panelest.jl Ratio\n10,000 0.01s 0.003s 0.3x вњ…\n100,000 0.10s 0.03s 0.3x вњ…\n1,000,000 2.0s 0.37s 0.2x вњ…\n10,000,000 21.6s 18.5s 0.9x вњ…\n\nSimple DGP, 3 fixed effects:\n\nObservations fixest Panelest.jl Ratio\n10,000 0.01s 0.004s 0.4x вњ…\n100,000 0.02s 0.03s 1.5x\n1,000,000 0.23s 0.57s 2.5x\n10,000,000 2.3s 2.1s 0.9x вњ…","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Results:-Poisson","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Results: Poisson","text":"Simple DGP, 2 fixed effects:\n\nObservations fixest Panelest.jl Ratio\n10,000 0.04s 0.03s 0.8x вњ…\n100,000 0.34s 0.51s 1.5x\n1,000,000 4.3s 6.4s 1.5x","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Results:-Logit","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Results: Logit","text":"Simple DGP, 2 fixed effects:\n\nObservations fixest Panelest.jl Ratio\n10,000 0.04s 0.03s 0.8x вњ…\n100,000 1.1s 0.33s 0.3x вњ…","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Implementation","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Implementation","text":"| | fixest | Panelest.jl | |-|вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“|вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“вЂ“-| | Language | R + C++ (Rcpp) | Pure Julia | | FE absorption | Custom C++ (Irons-Tuck) | Ported Julia (Irons-Tuck) | | Poisson solver | Berge concentrated likelihood | Concentrated likelihood + 2-FE cell trick | | Parallelism | Multi-threaded C++ | Julia Threads.@threads |","category":"section"},{"location":"tutorials/06_benchmarking/#Reproducing","page":"Benchmarking","title":"Reproducing","text":"cd Panelest.jl/benchmark/\njulia setup_data.jl   # generate data\nbash run_all.sh       # run Julia + R benchmarks\n\nResults land in benchmark/results/.","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#API-Reference","page":"Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Estimation-Functions","page":"Reference","title":"Estimation Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"reference/#Internal-Engine","page":"Reference","title":"Internal Engine","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Panelest.jl","page":"Home","title":"Panelest.jl","text":"Panelest.jl is a high-performance Julia package for panel data estimation. It is designed to match the speed and user-friendliness of R's fixest while leveraging Julia's native performance for non-linear models.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Features","page":"Home","title":"Features","text":"High-Performance IRLS-FE: Efficiently absorbs fixed effects within the iteratively reweighted least squares loop for Poisson, Logit, and Probit models.\nMultiple Fixed Effects: Support for high-dimensional individual and time fixed effects using FixedEffects.jl.\nFlexible Clustering: Robust and multi-way clustered standard errors via Vcov.jl.\nNon-Linear Panel Methods: Includes Chamberlain's Conditional Logit (recursive algorithm) and Wooldridge's Correlated Random Effects (CRE).","category":"section"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Home","title":"Installation","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"Panelest\")","category":"section"},{"location":"#Quick-Start","page":"Home","title":"Quick Start","text":"using Panelest, DataFrames, StatsModels, Vcov\n\n# OLS with fixed effects and clustered SE\nmodel = feols(df, @formula(y ~ x1 + fe(id) + fe(time)), vcov = Vcov.cluster(:id))\n\n# Poisson with fixed effects\nmodel_pois = fepois(df, @formula(y_count ~ x1 + fe(id)))","category":"section"}]
}
